With antiviral drugs, the scientific questions that need to be answered before the pandemic are not as daunting (

  13
 ). Originally, both classes of antiviral drugs were believed to be effective against a pandemic virus. Adamantane action is limited to type A viruses, but all pandemic viruses are type A (

  15
 ). The neuraminidases of many different type A viruses have been evaluated with respect to NAIs, and all have been found susceptible (

  1
 ). As a result, given advance planning so that supplies are available, antiviral drugs can be used early in a pandemic and do not require specific production and formulation. Because they are much less costly than NAIs, adamantanes were part of the overall antiviral strategy (

  20
 ). Having 2 classes of drug increased the amount of antiviral drugs available to stockpile since production limitations are an issue with the NAIs.
